Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Florida COVID-19 Trajectory

Roy Williams, Gabriel J. Odom, Zoran Bursac, and Mary Jo Trepka

Introduction

Public understanding of science is critical in times of crisis. The following analysis was conducted to examine the trajectory of COVID-19 in Florida. For phased reopening, the White House has set guidelines for local municipalities in their Opening Up American Again report. In the report, it is highly suggested that:

  1. Local areas show a downward trajectory in the number of positive cases as a percent of total tests over a two-week period, and
  2. Local hospitals have capacity to handle all patients without crisis care.

The analysis begins by looking at the number of new positive cases each day and the number of total tests performed each day. The figures are presented together because as there is more testing, there are likely to be more positive test results. Therefore, the proportion of positive cases is also calculated. Given either a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive cases is the key metric to be used when looking at epidemic trajectory. It is recommended that this proportion not exceed 5%.

The data above show for each day since June 8th: the number of positive COVID-19 tests, the number of negative COVID-19 tests, and the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests to total COVID-19 tests.

Total COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of total tests over the past two months (shown on a log scale):

The average number of COVID-19 tests performed each day has increased from under 35,000 in early June to almost 100,000 currently. On average, from 07 June until 22 July, there was an increase of approximately 1562 addition tests performed each day over the previous day. This data is presented on a log scale.

Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of positive tests over the past two months:

Over the past two weeks, there has been an average decrease of -73 positive cases each day, per day.

Positive COVID-19 Tests within the Past Two Weeks

In addition to the overall trend of positive COVID-19 tests shown above, we also show an enhanced view of the last two weeks, depicting a decrease in positive cases during this period of time.

Proportion of Positive Cases within Past Two Weeks

The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests for the past two weeks is:

During the 14-day period from 08 July to 22 July, there was a decrease in the proportion of positive COVID-19 cases reported in Florida. During this time, there was an average decrease of -0.2% per day for new positive cases. However, the percentage of positive test results obtained continues to exceed the 5% positive threshold recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO) for reopening.

Proportion of Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

These are the proportions of positive COVID-19 tests for the since the second week of June:

Overall, the proportion of positive test results out of all tests increased significantly from approximately 5% in early June. Additionally, this proportion has been consistently greater than 10% since June 22nd. This number is function of test availability and the population being tested. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, an increase in the proportion of positive tests obtained points to evidence of increased COVID-19 community spread in Florida.

COVID-19 Deaths by Day

Overall, deaths for Florida increased until mid April highs. Subsequently, there was a decline until approximately the first week of June. Afterwards, there has been an increase in the number of deaths per day for Florida, returning to highs observed in mid April.

Note: Due to delays in classifying the cause of death and thus of reporting deaths due to COVID-19, the most recent data will undercount the number of deaths. For this reason, the last two weeks were excluded from this analysis of deaths.

Conclusion

During the past two weeks, the number of positive COVID-19 tests obtained has decreased by an average of -73 each day. The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests has also decreased at 0.17% each day. While these trends are encouraging, the proportion of positive tests obtained has remained consistently greater than 10% since June 25th.

Data Sources

Data sources are as follows:

  • COVID-19 Test Results: The number of positive and negative COVID-19 test results come from the Florida Department of Health: https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
  • COVID-19 Hospital Census: The hospitalization data is disseminated by Floridas Agency for Health Care Administration: https://ahca.myflorida.com.
  • COVID-19 Death Linelist: This list is created and disseminated by Floridas Department of Health. Deaths are medical examiner confirmed. https://floridahealthcovid19.gov.
